00:10:40.439 --> 00:10:42.574 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> Leonardo da Vinci's painting,
 "The Last Supper",</i>

00:10:42.674 --> 00:10:44.543
reminds us of
that saying,

00:10:44.643 --> 00:10:47.479
"A picture is worth
a thousand words."

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:49.314
Well, that's
especially true

00:10:49.414 --> 00:10:51.550 align:start size:84% position:16%
when it comes to
remembering something.

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:53.819 align:start size:84% position:16%
Researchers at the
University of Waterloo,

00:10:53.919 --> 00:10:57.523 align:start size:91% position:9%
in Canada, say that drawing
is a powerful influence

00:10:57.623 --> 00:11:00.659
on our memory, and can
be especially useful

00:11:00.759 --> 00:11:04.363 align:start size:88% position:13%
for older adults and
even those with dementia.

00:11:04.463 --> 00:11:07.098 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> Researchers had participants
 draw quick pictures.</i>

00:11:07.199 --> 00:11:09.601
<i> Four second drawings
 of words in a list,</i>

00:11:09.701 --> 00:11:12.171
<i> such as truck and pear.</i>

00:11:12.271 --> 00:11:15.307 align:start position:0%
<i>Well, the people who drew
pictures remembered them better</i>

00:11:15.407 --> 00:11:18.544
<i> than when they wrote the
 word out multiple times.</i>

00:11:18.644 --> 00:11:20.712
<i> Creating the drawings
 was also more effective</i>

00:11:20.813 --> 00:11:22.414 align:start size:72% position:28%
<i> than imagining
 the items</i>

00:11:22.514 --> 00:11:24.683 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> or viewing pictures
 of the words.</i>

00:11:24.784 --> 00:11:27.018
Researchers also found
that drawing helps people

00:11:27.118 --> 00:11:29.188 align:start size:78% position:22%
remember even more
complex words.

00:11:29.288 --> 00:11:32.457 align:start size:97% position:3%
People who were given a minute
to draw an image of a spore

00:11:32.557 --> 00:11:34.493
were more likely
to remember it

00:11:34.593 --> 00:11:37.095
<i> than people who were asked
 to write out the definition.</i>

00:11:37.196 --> 00:11:39.865
Now, younger people were
better than older people

00:11:39.965 --> 00:11:42.768 align:start size:88% position:13%
at remembering the words
that they wrote out,

00:11:42.868 --> 00:11:45.170 align:start size:91% position:9%
but there was no difference
between the two groups

00:11:45.270 --> 00:11:48.140 align:start size:78% position:22%
as far as the words
they had drawn.

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:50.943 align:start size:91% position:9% line:76%
<i> Researchers asked 13 people
 diagnosed with dementia</i>

00:11:51.043 --> 00:11:54.813 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> to either draw or write
 60 words that were read aloud.</i>

00:11:54.913 --> 00:11:57.650
<i> The results showed a
 massive memory benefit</i>

00:11:57.750 --> 00:12:00.953 align:start size:94% position:6%
for words that had been drawn
rather than written.

00:12:01.053 --> 00:12:03.088 align:start size:84% position:16%
Now, in some cases,
the patient's drawings

00:12:03.188 --> 00:12:05.223
look like scribbles,
but it doesn't matter.

00:12:05.323 --> 00:12:07.860 align:start size:84% position:16%
Because drawing ability
has nothing to do

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:09.394
with memory performance.

00:12:09.495 --> 00:12:11.730
Even those of us who can
only draw stick figures

00:12:11.830 --> 00:12:14.567 align:start size:88% position:13%
can get memory benefits,
and here's why.

00:12:15.834 --> 00:12:17.102
<i> Retaining new information</i>

00:12:17.202 --> 00:12:18.938 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> typically declines
 as we age,</i>

00:12:19.038 --> 00:12:21.907 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> because of deterioration
 of critical brain structures</i>

00:12:22.007 --> 00:12:24.342 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> involved in memory,
 such as the hippocampus</i>

00:12:24.442 --> 00:12:25.811
<i> and frontal lobes.</i>

00:12:25.911 --> 00:12:29.581 align:start position:0%
<i>However, visual-spatial
processing regions of the brain</i>

00:12:29.682 --> 00:12:32.351 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> involved in representing
 images and pictures</i>

00:12:32.451 --> 00:12:35.121 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> remain mostly intact
 in normal aging</i>

00:12:35.221 --> 00:12:37.156
<i> and in dementia.</i>

00:12:37.256 --> 00:12:39.124
<i> Drawing makes use
 of brain regions</i>

00:12:39.224 --> 00:12:41.026
<i> that are still preserved,</i>

00:12:41.126 --> 00:12:43.662 align:start position:0%
<i>and could help people
experiencing memory impairment.</i>

00:12:44.829 --> 00:12:47.199
These findings will likely
lead to new interventions

00:12:47.299 --> 00:12:49.734
and therapies to help
dementia patients,

00:12:49.835 --> 00:12:54.373
and all of us, hold on
to valuable memories.

00:12:54.473 --> 00:12:59.110 align:start size:6% position:94% line:0%
